               The Ciuile lawes decre that the yſſue euer foloweth the wōbe, that is to ſaye, the mother. As for example, yf a bōd woman be marryed to a freman, theyr iſſue ſhalbe bond. And contrarywiſe if a bonde man marrie a free woman, he begetteth none but free children But the lawe of Englād neuer iudgeth the iſſu to folowe the mothers condicion, but alwaye the fathers. So that a free man begetteth free children aſwell of a bonde woman as of a free woman: and a bōde mā in wedlock cā beget nōe other but bōd

childrē. Whether of theſe lawes is better thynke you in theier ſentences. It is a cruell lawe which without offēce ſubdueth the free mans chylde to bōdage. And no leſſe crueltie is to be thought in ye lawe, whiche without anye deſerte oppreſſeth the free womās chylde with bōdage. Yet the Ciuiliās ſaye that ye Ciuile lawes in theſe their iudgemēts do excell. For an euil tree ſaye they can not brynge furthe good fruites, nor a good tree beare euyll fruites. And by the cōſēt of all lawes it is agreed that euery plante yeldeth to the nature of ye groūde wherein it is planted the chylde alſo hath muche more certeī &amp; ſure knowlege of ye mother thē of ye
                  
father, Whereunto the lawyers of Englande aū
